* littext.pkg -- installation manifest for the littext package
*
* This file is read by Stata's net command when a user runs
*
*     net install littext
*
* Comment lines begin with an asterisk in column 1; no other comment
* syntax is recognized by the manifest grammar.
*
* File-declaration directives:
*
*   f <path>   Declares a file. Stata decides its fate by suffix:
*              .ado and .sthlp are INSTALLED into the adopath; every
*              other suffix is treated as an ANCILLARY file, which a
*              plain "net install" / "ssc install" does NOT install --
*              it is copied to the user's working directory only on an
*              explicit "net get" or "ssc install ..., all".
*
*   F <path>   FORCE-installs the file into the adopath regardless of
*              suffix, so that findfile can locate it at run time no
*              matter the user's current working directory.
*
* The Python pipeline modules are therefore declared with F: the .ado
* layer imports them at run time and must be able to find them after a
* default install. The "python/" path component is the FETCH path
* relative to the net-from location; it is NOT reproduced as a
* subdirectory of the adopath on install. The .ado layer must locate
* each module with findfile rather than by constructing a "python/"
* path of its own.
*
v 3
d littext: automated construct discovery and relationship inference from academic text
d
d {bf:littext} extracts candidate construct relationships from a corpus
d of academic text (titles, abstracts, full texts). It produces three
d Stata frames -- lt_constructs, lt_relations, lt_diag -- holding the
d extracted constructs, candidate relationships with confidence scores
d and evidence sentences, and per-document diagnostics. A companion
d {bf:littext graph} command produces ten visualization types (five
d Stata-native, five matplotlib).
d
d The pipeline combines spaCy noun-chunk extraction, sentence-
d transformer embeddings, HDBSCAN synonym clustering, normalized
d pointwise mutual information for relationship candidacy, and a
d six-pattern dependency-arc matcher for relationship valence.
d
d Requires Stata 19 with Python integration configured. Required
d Python packages: spacy, sentence-transformers, hdbscan, scikit-learn,
d umap-learn, matplotlib, networkx, plotly, pandas, numpy. Optional package
d for the addsentiment option: vaderSentiment. Run {stata littext
d install, verbose} after installation to check the Python
d environment.
d
d Author: Nebojsa S. Davcik, EM Normandie Business School
d Support: davcik@live.com
d ORCID: 0000-0003-1041-8788
d
d Distribution-Date: 20260615
d
* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
* Top-level Stata files: dispatchers, subcommand handlers, help, and alias.
* Installed by suffix (.ado, .sthlp), so lowercase f is correct here.
* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
f littext.ado
f littext.sthlp
f litt.ado
f litt.sthlp
f _littext_install.ado
f _littext_analyze.ado
f _littext_graph.ado
f _littext_example.ado
f _littext_export.ado
f _littext_resolve.ado
*
* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
* Python pipeline. Force-installed (F) so a default net install places
* them on the adopath where findfile can locate them. Filenames are
* case-sensitive. 
* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
F python/__init__.py
F python/littext_env.py
F python/littext_run.py
F python/littext_pipeline.py
F python/littext_extract.py
F python/littext_embed.py
F python/littext_cluster.py
F python/littext_relate.py
F python/littext_cleaners.py
F python/littext_hierarchy.py
F python/littext_io.py
F python/littext_state.py
F python/littext_viz.py
*
* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
* Licence. Force-installed so the GPL text accompanies the code on a
* default install (GPL conveyance best practice).
* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
F LICENSE
*
* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
* Documentation. Ancillary (f): fetched on "net get" / "ssc install,
* all". The authoritative copies live in the GitHub repository.
* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
f README.md
f CHANGELOG.md
f CITATION.cff
*
* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
* Example data. The corpus .dta is force-installed (F) so
* _littext_example.ado can findfile it at run time after a flattened
* install, exactly like the Python modules. The CSV / XLSX mirrors and
* the corpus README are ancillary (f): human-facing provenance, never
* read by the package.
* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
F data/littext_example.dta
f data/littext_rbv_synth_v01_abstracts.csv
f data/littext_rbv_synth_v01.xlsx
f data/littext_rbv_synth_v01_README.md
*
* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
* NOT shipped via this manifest:
*   python/__pycache__/*.pyc   Build artifacts; never distribute. Add
*                              __pycache__/ to .gitignore.
*   tests/*.py                 Developer regression suite; lives in the
*                              repository, not the installed footprint.
* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
